  "text": "To understand what processes are affected in the atipt1;3;5;7 quadruple mutant, we examined the anatomy in root sections at a basal position. The Arabidopsis root is formed with an invariant radial pattern, consisting of single layers of epidermis, cortex, endodermis, pericycle, and the vasculature [CITATION_1] . Later the cambium forms, which produces cells forming secondary xylemand phloem-containing tissue, the latter constituting the area outside the cambial zone ( Fig. S2 and Fig. 2A ). The atipt1;3;5;7 quadruple mutant lacks the vascular cambium altogether in the root (Fig. 2B and Fig. S2 ). Whereas WT roots continuously underwent secondary growth, atipt1;3;5;7 mutant plants exhibited no secondary growth until at least 21 days after germination (Fig. S2) .",
